04798nam a22008055i 9780814739167DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780814739167  a(DE-B1597)547270  a(OCoLC)779828117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1992.6b.B495 2008 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a302.23/452221 aBielby, Denise D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGlobal TV :bExporting Television and Culture in the World Market /cDenise D. Bielby, C. Lee Harrington. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Syndication Market in U.S. Television -- t2 Television in the Global Market -- t3 The (Continued) Relevance of Genre -- t4 Managing Television’s Cultural Properties -- t5 Discourses of Distribution -- tConclusion -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA reporter for the Los Angeles Times once noted that “I Love Lucy is said to be on the air somewhere in the world 24 hours a day.” That Lucy’s madcap antics can be watched anywhere at any time is thanks to television syndication, a booming global marketplace that imports and exports TV shows. Programs from different countries are packaged, bought, and sold all over the world, under the watch of an industry that is extraordinarily lucrative for major studios and production companies.In Global TV, Denise D. Bielb and C. Lee Harrington seek to understand the machinery of this marketplace, its origins and history, its inner workings, and its product management. In so doing, they are led to explore the cultural significance of this global trade, and to ask how it is so remarkably successful despite the inherent cultural differences between shows and local audiences. How do culture-specific genres like American soap operas and Latin telenovelas so easily cross borders and adapt to new cultural surroundings? Why is The Nanny, whose gum-chewing star is from Queens, New York, a smash in Italy? Importantly, Bielby and Harrington also ask which kinds of shows fail. What is lost in translation? Considering such factors as censorship and other such state-specific policies, what are the inevitable constraints of crossing over?Highly experienced in the field, Bielby and Harrington provide a unique and richly textured look at global television through a cultural lens, one that has an undeniable and complex effect on what shows succeed and which do not on an international scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspects. 0aTelevision programsxMarketing. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aSeeks.  aglobal.  ahistory.  ainner.  amachinery.  amanagement.  amarketplace.  aorigins.  aproduct.  atelevision.  aunderstand.  aworkings.1 aHarrington, C. Lee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479941340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739167423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814739167/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5